	   <tr><td colspan=2>warrior vs monk.&nbsp;&nbsp;It really depends on what you want to do, and how you want to play.  I love being a monk, and when I can't pull, I am bored out of my mind.  If the main reason that you want to play is to chat with other players, then a monk is not the class for you.  You really can't talk and pull, it's a fact.  You're too busy running, navigating tunnels, feigning, calling inc, and letting your gruop know how many you have.  The only time that you will be talking is during the battle itself, you know, that couple of seconds while you wait for kick to recycle.  Warriors are occasionally allowed to pull.  It depends on the group and the circemstances.  ie.  three sk's in Charsis, the warrior pulls, 'cause the monk would die with that many HT's.   I know.  I've died that way  =(  <br>   In big raids it's important for the monk to know what he's pulling what the spawn points/times are, whether or not there is a wanderer that will agro, and they have to know exactly how good their chanter is.  'cause if you pull mobs that the chanter can't mez, you can all die.  A monk also needs to know when to eat the pull, just get to a safe spot and die.  <br>   A warrior can be an enchanters best friend, if they know what to attack and when to attack it.  Lets use the plane of fear as an example.  say the monk brings in an Amy, a TT (ae dispell), and two scareling.   The warrior that kills the Amy first and the TT last will be well liked by the enchanter.  If the warrior attacks the TT after the Amy, it will do it's AE dispell breaking the mez on the scarelings, which could well mean dead enchanters.  Dead enchanters often mean dead groups.  It's an ugly thing. <br>   Due to the gear limitations on monks, at high lvl's you will often see Warriors with Ac that is equal to, if not greater than that of a monk.  As to weapon restrictions, well lets just say that monks only have to worry about keeping three skills up to par, and our blunts are the best weapons in the game.  second to our fists once you get the epic of course.   <br>&nbsp;<br> </td></tr>
